The family of former Liberian president Charles Taylor expressed concerns over the imbalance in legal representation, with the prosecution having more senior counsels than the defense.
They also criticized the installation of video surveillance in The Hague, violating Taylor's privacy.
Taylor's lawyers demanded more time to prepare for the war crimes trial, citing insufficient resources and the need for additional senior counsels.
Witnesses were hesitant to testify due to fear of UN sanctions.
The trial, moved to The Hague for security reasons, faced delays as the defense sought more time and resources.
